    "summary": "The First Bulgarian Empire (681–1018 AD) was the first major Slavic state in the Balkans — a powerful medieval kingdom that challenged Byzantine dominance in southeastern Europe and at its peak under Simeon I (r. 893–927 AD) nearly captured Constantinople itself, making its ruler the most powerful monarch in Europe outside the Islamic world. Founded by the Bulgars (a Turkic people from the Eurasian steppe) who merged with the existing Slavic population of the northeastern Balkans, Bulgaria developed rapidly into a Slavic-Bulgarian Orthodox Christian state after its conversion in 864 AD under Khan Boris I.\n\nBulgaria's cultural significance extended beyond its political power: Saints Cyril and Methodius (Byzantine missionaries who created the Glagolitic alphabet, predecessor to Cyrillic) had been sent originally to Moravia; when their mission was expelled, their disciples found refuge in Bulgaria under Boris I's patronage. Bulgaria became the center for the translation and dissemination of Christian texts in the Slavic languages using the Cyrillic script — making Bulgaria the origin point of Slavic Orthodox Christian literary culture that spread to Serbia, Russia, and beyond. Simeon I achieved the title of 'Emperor of the Bulgars and the Romans' and made Bulgaria a major cultural center (the 'Preslav Literary School'). The First Empire was destroyed by Byzantine emperor Basil II ('the Bulgar-Slayer') in 1018 AD, when he blinded 15,000 Bulgarian prisoners — a deed that gave him his epithet.",
